}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90790"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a four-week history of a painless swelling in her neck. It appeared over a few days and has not changed in size since then. She has no other symptoms. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well. The lump is smooth-surfaced, soft and compressible (Image). There are no other adjacent lumps and no other visible lesions. Examination of the oropharynx is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lymphoma","Metastatic deposit","Submandibular duct calculus","Thyroglossal cyst","Branchial cyst"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen a patient presents with a painless swelling in the neck, malignancy must always be considered. Metastatic deposits in cervical nodes will most often originate from head and neck cancers (upper cervical nodes), skin cancers and thoracic-abdominal cancers (supraclavicular nodes). In this case, this is a typical history and physical appearance of a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebranchial cyst\u003C/strong\u003E. In addition, the physical finding are not typical of nodal enlargement. \u003Cstrong\u003EMetastatic deposits\u003C/strong\u003E tends to be firm and often multiple. \u003Cstrong\u003ELymphoma\u003C/strong\u003Etous nodes tends to have a rubbery consistence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst branchial cysts develop from embryonic remnants of a branchial cleft (most commonly the second cleft), they do not usually present until early adulthood. Sometimes they can present as an intermittent and painful swelling during an upper respiratory tract infection, but more often the swelling is painless and unchanging in size. The swelling is situated on the anterior border of the sternocleidomastoid muscle, thus excluding a submandibular gland enlargement\u003Cstrong\u003E (eg. submandibular duct calculus) \u003C/strong\u003Eand\u003Cstrong\u003E thyroglossal cyst\u003C/strong\u003E as possible diagnoses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most branchial cysts do not become apparent until the third or fourth decades of life."],"references":["Rosa PA, Hirsch DL, Dierks EJ. Congenital Neck Masses. Oral Maxillofacial Clin N Am 2008;20:339-52. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18603195/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74880"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1438"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15344"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15344"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/eda6d712-3c9b-44b9-a3b2-169f00d92ea3.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/eda6d712-3c9b-44b9-a3b2-169f00d92ea3.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74880","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74880"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T16:00:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T16:00:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1438"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90790"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"